### Conclusion

- In this investigation, the victims of this attack were nick montgomery, tricia becker, and everret french. These victims had their devices compromised.
- The attacker then attempted to create files on each victim’s shared folders, but all attempts failed. This confirmed an attempt at lateral movement, in which the attacker sought to establish persistence via the **`autorun.inf`** and **`desktop.ini`** files to infect folders with malicious scripts.
- After this attempt, the attacker proceeded to download a payload onto Nick Montgomery’s device, where he made a GET request to a malicious domain, **`www.ajaxmatters.com`**, which had a rating of 6/94 on VirusTotal. After analyzing the hash of a .dll file transferred during this process, I discovered it had a rating of 57/70, thus confirming the malicious payload.
- tricia.becker was infected with Formbook/XLoader, delivered via 156.96.154.210 as a .jpg file containing a DLL with reversed bytes, with C2 traffic to katchybugonsale.com
- everett.french was infected with Emotet, downloaded from dalgahavuzu.com via 178.211.56.194, with subsequent C2 communication observed
- Finally, the attacker launched a phishing campaign, in which they compromised the email account of the user "nick.montgomery" by sending an attachment to the email address **`conniebanner28@yahoo.com`**. This attachment contained an XLSM file, an Excel file that supports script execution—a common method used by attackers to distribute malware.
